I) Quality Control and Read Trimming with Fastp
Raw paired-end RNA-seq reads were processed using Fastp to remove adapter sequences and low-quality bases.  Generates quality-control reports for each sample.

Command:

fastp \
-i sample_R1.fastq.gz \
-I sample_R2.fastq.gz \
-o sample_R1.trimmed.fastq.gz \
-O sample_R2.trimmed.fastq.gz \
-h sample_report.html \
-j sample_report.json

II) Genome Index Generation with STAR
Reference genome was indexed using STAR together with the corresponding gene annotation (GTF) file. Allows STAR to efficiently align RNA-seq reads and detect splice junctions.

Command:

STAR \
--runMode genomeGenerate \
--genomeDir genome_index \
--genomeFastaFiles reference_genome.fasta \
--sjdbGTFfile annotation.gtf \
--genomeSAindexNbases 13 \
--genomeChrBinNbits 16

III) Read Alignment with STAR
Trimmed reads were aligned to the reference genome using STAR in two-pass mode. Two-pass approach improves splice junction detection and alignment accuracy. Aligned reads written to coordinate-sorted BAM files.

Command:

STAR \
--genomeDir genome_index \
--readFilesIn sample_R1.trimmed.fastq.gz sample_R2.trimmed.fastq.gz \
--readFilesCommand zcat \
--runThreadN 16 \
--twopassMode Basic \
--outSAMtype BAM SortedByCoordinate \
--outFileNamePrefix sample_

IV) Duplicate Read Removal
Duplicate reads generated during PCR amplification were removed using SAMtools. Reduction of potential biases in downstream analyses.

Command:

samtools markdup -r \
sample.sorted.bam \
sample.markdup.bam
V) Mapping Quality Filtering and BAM Indexing

Reads with mapping quality scores below 30 were removed to retain only confidently aligned reads. The filtered BAM files were then indexed for efficient access to genomic regions.

Command:

samtools view \
-b \
-q 30 \
sample.markdup.bam \
-o sample.unique.bam

samtools index sample.unique.bam

VI) Generation of BigWig Coverage Files
Coverage tracks were generated using deepTools (bamCoverage) and normalized using RPKM. The resulting BigWig files can be visualized in genome browsers such as IGV.

Command:

bamCoverage \
-b sample.unique.bam \
-o sample.bw \
--normalizeUsing RPKM


VII) Gene Quantification with FeatureCounts
Following read alignment and BAM file processing, gene-level read counts were generated using FeatureCounts. 
Assigns aligned reads to annotated genes and produces a count matrix that serves as the input for differential expression analysis.

Command:

featureCounts \
-T 8 \
-p \
-a annotation.gtf \
-o gene_counts.txt \
mapping_results/*.bam

Notes:
-p is used for paired-end RNA-seq data.
gene_counts.txt contains the number of reads assigned to each gene for every sample.

VIII) Differential Expression Analysis with DESeq2
Differential expression analysis was performed using DESeq2 in R. 
DESeq2 normalizes read counts, models count variation between biological replicates, and identifies genes that are significantly differentially expressed between experimental groups.


R script : 
library(DESeq2)

# Read count matrix
countData <- read.table("gene_counts.txt", header = TRUE, row.names = 1)

# Read sample metadata
colData <- read.csv("sample_metadata.csv", row.names = 1)

# Create DESeq2 dataset
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = countData, colData = colData, design = ~ condition)

# Run differential expression analysis
dds <- DESeq(dds)

# Extract results
res <- results(dds)

# Save results
write.csv(as.data.frame(res), file = "DESeq2_results.csv")

The resulting output("DESeq2_results.csv") contains log2 fold changes, p-values, and adjusted p-values (FDR) for each gene, 
allowing identification of genes that are differentially expressed between the conditions being compared.


IX) Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
To visualize sample clustering and assess whether biological replicates group together.

R script :
vsd <- vst(dds)
plotPCA(vsd, intgroup="condition")

X) Volcano Plot
Visualizes significantly upregulated and downregulated genes.

R script :
plot(res$log2FoldChange, -log10(res$padj))

